</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Tecla_Input_Method">Tecla Input Method</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Features">Features</span></h3>
<ul>
<li> Acts as a standard soft keyboard when no accessibility options are selected
</li>
<li> Receives switch event broadcast (intents) from the <a href="/Tecla_Access/Switch_Event_Provider" title="Tecla Access/Switch Event Provider">Switch Event Provider (SEP)</a> and uses them to navigate, select and forward key events (D-pad, hardware buttons, keyboard) to the OS via scanning.
</li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="ToDo">ToDo</span></h3>
<ul>
<li> Provide container for alternative access methods (e.g. Morse).
</li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Implementation_Notes">Implementation Notes</span></h3>
<p>Important notes on implementation are included here. For a list of implementation requirements and details on the alternatives explored visit the <a href="/Talk:Tecla_Access/App" title="Talk:Tecla Access/App">discussion page</a>.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Explicitly_hiding.2Fshowing_the_soft_input_method">Explicitly hiding/showing the soft input method</span></h4>
<p>The IME Service class offers the following methods:
</p>
<pre>
showWindow(boolean force)
hideWindow()
</pre>
<p>Although these methods are not well documented, we managed to use them to achieve our goals. the <code>force</code> boolean in the first method seems to be the difference between a request and a forced action.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Highlighting">Highlighting</span></h4>
<p>This was done by manipulating the <code>pressed</code> property of key objects in the Tecla IME. A drawable was used to implement the background color change.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Sending_Individual_Keys_to_an_Application">Sending Individual Keys to an Application</span></h4>
<p>A method was created to emulate hardware key events, the following example sends a DPAD UP key to an application:
</p>
<pre>
getCurrentInputConnection().sendKeyEvent(new KeyEvent(KeyEvent.ACTION_DOWN, KeyEvent.KEYCODE_DPAD_UP));
getCurrentInputConnection().sendKeyEvent(new KeyEvent(KeyEvent.ACTION_UP, KeyEvent.KEYCODE_DPAD_UP));
</pre>
<p>However, these events cannot send key events to overlays such as the application's options menu and some pop-ups. There are still no known solutions for <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://bugs.launchpad.net/meadl/+bug/617060">this issue</a>.
</p>
